          "settings": {
            "heading": "Writing Style, Themes, and Storytelling Approach",
            "body": "<p>Rowling’s writing style balances clarity with imagination. Her prose is accessible yet layered, allowing younger readers to enter the story while offering deeper themes for adults. She structures her narratives around mystery, gradually revealing information through clues, foreshadowing, and emotional turning points.</p><p>Recurring themes in her work include friendship, belonging, prejudice, power, and the consequences of choice. At the heart of her stories is the idea that love and loyalty are forces stronger than fear, giving her fantasy a moral and emotional depth.</p>"
          }
        },
        "list_block_hDNtNV": {
          "type": "list_block",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "J.K. Rowling’s Works in Collector and Leather-Bound Editions",
            "intro": "<p>Spanning from the founding of the empire by Babur in 1526 to its formal dissolution in 1857, the book is organized into six thematic parts:</p>",
            "list_items": "Part I — The Foundations: Babur, Humayun, and the Central Asian inheritance\nPart II — The Consolidation: Akbar's administrative and cultural revolution\nPart III — The Imperial Zenith: Jahangir and Shah Jahan — art, architecture, and power\nPart IV — The Orthodoxy and Its Consequences: Aurangzeb and the politics of religion\nPart V — The Long Decline: The later Mughals and the rise of regional powers\nPart VI — The Twilight Empire: From 1803 to the Revolt of 1857"
          }
        }
